huntMaster.HARVEST_REPORTING: Required: Any harvested cougar must be checked by a DWR employee within 48 hours of the date of kill. The DWR employee will affix a permanent possession tag to the pelt or unskinned carcass. You may not possess an unskinned carcass or green pelt after the 48 hour check-in period. If you need to reach a Division employee after regular business hours, over a weekend, or on a holiday, contact your local police dispatch. In addition, you cannot ship a green pelt out of the state of Utah or present it to a taxidermist if the pelt does not have a permanent possession tag attached.

huntBoundaryInfos.LAND_OWNERSHIP: Grand Staircase Escalante National Monument, SITLA
huntBoundaryInfos.CAMPGRND_INFO: Please direct all questions regarding maps and camping regulations to the Grand Staircase Escalante National Monument at the Kanab BLM Field Office.
huntBoundaryInfos.ATV_VEH_ACCESS: All roads and ATV trails on this unit are managed by the GSENM and SITLA and regulations are covered in their Travel Management Plans.  Please direct all questions regarding which roads and trails ATVs can be operated on to the Kanab GSENM/BLM Field Office.
huntBoundaryInfos.BOUNDARY_DESCRIPTION: Garfield and Kane counties--Boundary begins at the Paria River and the Utah-Arizona state line; north along the Paria River to SR-12; east on SR-12 to the Burr Trail road at Boulder; southeast on this road to Lake Powell; southwest along the shore of Lake Powell to the Utah-Arizona state line; west along this state line to the Paria River. USGS 1:100,000 Maps: Escalante, Navajo Mountain, Smoky Mountain. Boundary questions? Call the Cedar City office, 435-865-6100

Emery, Sevier, and Wayne counties--Boundary begins at the crossing of I-70 over the Green River; south along the Green River to the Colorado River; south along the Colorado River and the west shoreline of Lake Powell to SR-95; north on SR-95 to a point two miles south of Hanksville and the SR- 95/SR-24 Jct; west along a line two miles south of SR-24 to a point on the Notom road two miles south of SR-24; north on this road to SR-24; east on this road to Caineville and the Caineville Wash road; north along this road to the Cathedral Valley road; west on this road to Rock Springs Bench and the Last Chance Desert road; north on this road to the Blue Flats road; north and east on this road to the Willow Springs road; north on this road towards Windy Peak and the Windy Peak road; west on this road to SR- 72, I-70, and the SR-10 junction; north on SR-10 to SR-6 at Price; east on SR-6 to I-70; east on this road to the crossing of the Green River. EXCLUDES ALL NATIONAL PARKS. USGS 1:100,000 Maps: Escalante, Loa, Hanksville, Hite Crossing, Huntington, Salina, San Rafael Desert. Boundary questions? Call the Price office, 435-613-3700.

huntBoundaryInfos.LAND_OWNERSHIP: The vast majority of the unit is public land.  The exception is the Green River Valley near the town of Green River
huntBoundaryInfos.CAMPGRND_INFO: There are no developed campgrounds on the unit.  Plenty of dispersed camping opportunities exist on BLM lands.  Most people camp along the lower Price River east of Woodside, along the Green River north of the town of Green River or in Tushar Canyon
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIM_ACCESS_PTS: The Horse Canyon road is accessed off of SR-6 25 miles south of Price; the lower Price River road can be accessed off of SR-6 at the town of Woodside; the Hastings Road will access the east side of the Green River and can be found on the east side of the town of Green River, the Sego Canyon road is at the eastern boundary of the unit and is accessed in the town of Thompson.  Numerous small roads will access the mouths of Tushar, Coal, Horse, and Floy canyons.

huntBoundaryInfos.BOUNDARY_DESCRIPTION: Emery and Grand counties--Boundary begins at I-70 and US-6; east on I-70 to the Thompson Canyon road at Thompson; north on this road to the Sego Canyon road; north on this road to the Ute Indian Reservation boundary; west along this boundary to the Green River; north along this river to Range Creek; northwest along this creek to the Turtle Canyon/Little Park road;  west and north on this road to the Horse Canyon road; west on this road to US-6; south on US-6 to I-70.  EXCLUDES ALL NATIVE AMERICAN TRUST LANDS WITHIN THIS BOUNDARY. Excludes all CWMUs. USGS 1:100,000 Maps: Huntington, Price, Moab, Westwater. Boundary questions? Call the Price office, 435-613-3700.
huntBoundaryInfos.BOUNDARY_NAME: Book Cliffs, Rattlesnake Canyon/Nine Mile, South

huntBoundaryInfos.BOUNDARY_DESCRIPTION: San Juan County--Boundary begins at the confluence of the San Juan and Colorado rivers; north along the Colorado River to SR-95 near Hite Crossing; southeast on SR-95 to Fortknocker Canyon Road; southeast along this road to Woodenshoe Road; east along this road to Found Mesa Road (CR-2271); south and west along this road to SR-95; southeast on SR-95 to SR-261; south on SR-261 to SR-163; south on SR-163 to the San Juan River; west along this river to the Colorado River. EXCLUDES ALL NATIVE AMERICAN TRUST LANDS WITHIN THIS BOUNDARY. EXCLUDES ALL NATIONAL PARKS. USGS 1:100,000 Maps: Blanding, Bluff, Hanksville, Hite Crossing, Navajo Mountain. Boundary questions? Call the Price office, 435-613- 3700.
